00:00:57.479 --> 00:00:58.270
BILL NYE: Oh, yeah.

00:00:58.270 --> 00:01:00.000
Oh, yeah.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:01.580
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So
we're very concerned

00:01:01.580 --> 00:01:04.559
about public perceptions
of science, as are you.

00:01:04.559 --> 00:01:06.350
And there's some really
depressing numbers.

00:01:06.350 --> 00:01:08.100
I'm just going to go
through them rapidly.

00:01:08.100 --> 00:01:11.370
So first of all, only
40-some percent of Americans

00:01:11.370 --> 00:01:13.850
right now believe
that global warming

00:01:13.850 --> 00:01:16.354
is caused by human activity.

00:01:16.354 --> 00:01:18.020
BILL NYE: Less than
half is our problem.

00:01:18.020 --> 00:01:18.440
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Less than half.

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:20.140
BILL NYE: When it comes to
elections, that's a big deal.

00:01:20.140 --> 00:01:21.130
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Oh.

00:01:21.130 --> 00:01:22.120
BILL NYE: No, it is.

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:23.370
That's what I'm talking about.

00:01:23.370 --> 00:01:25.350
VIKRAM BAJAJ: And as
a consequence of that,

00:01:25.350 --> 00:01:28.080
very few people actually
believe that this is a problem

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:30.760
that we'll face
in our lifetimes.

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:31.945
And--

00:01:31.945 --> 00:01:34.240
BILL NYE: Oh, you'll see.

00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:35.115
Yeah.

00:01:35.115 --> 00:01:35.865
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So--

00:01:35.865 --> 00:01:37.420
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:37.420 --> 00:01:40.130
BILL NYE: No, I mean,
it's a big deal.

00:01:40.130 --> 00:01:43.590
VIKRAM BAJAJ: In the
case of human evolution,

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:45.220
we also have a similar problem.

00:01:45.220 --> 00:01:48.140
Only 19% of Americans,
according to Gallup,

00:01:48.140 --> 00:01:51.630
believe in the unfettered
human evolution

00:01:51.630 --> 00:01:53.910
driven by natural physical laws.

00:01:53.910 --> 00:01:56.610
There's about 30% who
believe in something called

00:01:56.610 --> 00:01:59.030
intelligent design, and
about a constant number

00:01:59.030 --> 00:02:01.530
who believe that
we were all created

00:02:01.530 --> 00:02:05.150
6,000 years ago, in an instant.

00:02:05.150 --> 00:02:08.840
And another consequence
of this is really

00:02:08.840 --> 00:02:10.900
how it's being
taught in schools.

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:13.120
Here in red, you
see all the states

00:02:13.120 --> 00:02:15.960
where there is no mention
of human evolution

00:02:15.960 --> 00:02:17.650
in the formal school curricula.

00:02:17.650 --> 00:02:19.670
Some mention biological
evolution, but not

00:02:19.670 --> 00:02:24.115
human evolution, not
evolution of mankind.

00:02:24.115 --> 00:02:24.615
And--

00:02:24.615 --> 00:02:25.823
BILL NYE: He means humankind.

00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:33.700
No, I mean, it's
just a new habit.

00:02:33.700 --> 00:02:36.100
For example, my mom was a
woman, just for example.

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:39.920
She's right there.

00:02:43.070 --> 00:02:44.000
It's not unusual.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.305
No.

00:02:46.305 --> 00:02:50.910
VIKRAM BAJAJ: But we'll ask
you about her later, actually.

00:02:50.910 --> 00:02:53.600
So there's also a
depressing trend

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:56.680
to use public taxpayer
money, taxpayer dollars,

00:02:56.680 --> 00:03:00.260
to fund creation education
in public schools

00:03:00.260 --> 00:03:03.200
in several states, in charter
schools, in voucher schools.

00:03:03.200 --> 00:03:05.240
And of course, there are
mainstream politicians

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:07.890
who don't believe
in this at all.

00:03:07.890 --> 00:03:09.057
Now--

00:03:09.057 --> 00:03:10.890
BILL NYE: You have the
picture of the guys--

00:03:10.890 --> 00:03:14.570
how many of you running for
president believe in evolution?

00:03:14.570 --> 00:03:15.710
Three of them don't.

00:03:15.710 --> 00:03:16.460
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Yes.

00:03:16.460 --> 00:03:17.090
BILL NYE: Can you imagine--

00:03:17.090 --> 00:03:19.298
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Three of the
four Republican governors.

00:03:19.298 --> 00:03:23.069
BILL NYE: --if these guys
got to be in charge-- well,

00:03:23.069 --> 00:03:23.860
they are in charge.

00:03:23.860 --> 00:03:24.610
They're governors.

00:03:27.770 --> 00:03:29.570
The most technically
advanced-- at least

00:03:29.570 --> 00:03:33.459
the biggest innovations, like
Google, come out of the US.

00:03:33.459 --> 00:03:35.000
And to have people
that don't believe

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:36.950
in the process of
science running the show

00:03:36.950 --> 00:03:39.579
is just a formula for disaster.

00:03:39.579 --> 00:03:40.620
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Absolutely.

00:03:40.620 --> 00:03:41.880
BILL NYE: It is.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:44.570
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So Google
is a scientific company.

00:03:44.570 --> 00:03:47.420
We're very science
driven, quantitative.

00:03:47.420 --> 00:03:51.650
And this is particularly
depressing to us.

00:03:51.650 --> 00:03:53.204
Here's belief in evolution--

00:03:53.204 --> 00:03:54.578
BILL NYE: Oh,
gosh, look at this.

00:04:02.140 --> 00:04:04.610
VIKRAM BAJAJ: And I know that
some of your recent criticism

00:04:04.610 --> 00:04:07.790
of pseudo science,
in general, really

00:04:07.790 --> 00:04:10.680
is based on arguments of
economic competitiveness.

00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:12.500
BILL NYE: For me, it is, yeah.

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:15.300
Like you guys-- how many of you
watch "The Science Guy" show?

00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:16.486
AUDIENCE: [CHEERING]

00:04:16.486 --> 00:04:19.066
BILL NYE: I love
you, man, woman.

00:04:19.066 --> 00:04:23.820
No, so if we produce a
generation of science students

00:04:23.820 --> 00:04:25.820
that don't believe
in science, you're

00:04:25.820 --> 00:04:29.319
not going to have the next
Google, whatever that is.

00:04:29.319 --> 00:04:30.860
You will not have
the next generation

00:04:30.860 --> 00:04:32.750
of employees at Google.

00:04:32.750 --> 00:04:37.360
Texas Instruments had to
advertise for, I guess,

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:40.970
engineers in Maryland,
because they were concerned--

00:04:40.970 --> 00:04:44.685
Texas Instruments is not called
Maryland Instruments-- because

00:04:44.685 --> 00:04:49.405
of the quality of the Maryland
school system in comparison.

00:04:49.405 --> 00:04:50.740
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Absolutely.

00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:52.944
So hopefully, you'll
help us, you'll arm us--

00:04:52.944 --> 00:04:53.860
BILL NYE: It's all me.

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:54.360
Yeah.

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:56.520
VIKRAM BAJAJ: with
instruments to fight this,

00:04:56.520 --> 00:04:58.290
because our reaction
in observing this

00:04:58.290 --> 00:05:02.320
is to be pretty depressed.

00:05:02.320 --> 00:05:05.360
We don't know how exactly
to counteract these forces.

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:06.930
We hope you'll
teach us about that.

00:05:06.930 --> 00:05:09.940
Maybe, actually, this
would be more appropriate,

00:05:09.940 --> 00:05:12.520
considering the subject
of our conversation today.

00:05:12.520 --> 00:05:14.270
BILL NYE: For those
of you who don't know,

00:05:14.270 --> 00:05:18.360
that's my old boss there.

00:05:18.360 --> 00:05:19.850
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So
let's begin there.

00:05:19.850 --> 00:05:25.270
We can remove our
friend from the screen.

00:05:25.270 --> 00:05:27.610
BILL NYE: That's not
really my old boss.

00:05:27.610 --> 00:05:31.360
It's a guy I used
to sit next to.

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:33.870
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So my first
question is really an easy one.

00:05:33.870 --> 00:05:35.240
You've seen the numbers.

00:05:35.240 --> 00:05:36.810
Now, you're a science educator.

00:05:36.810 --> 00:05:37.970
I'm a scientist.

00:05:37.970 --> 00:05:40.690
Are those dismal
numbers a failure

00:05:40.690 --> 00:05:42.180
of my profession or yours?

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:43.260
BILL NYE: Oh, it's me.

00:05:43.260 --> 00:05:45.850
It's all me.

00:05:45.850 --> 00:05:48.860
What's happened in the
US is the people teaching

00:05:48.860 --> 00:05:52.790
or asked to teach science
are not especially qualified

00:05:52.790 --> 00:05:55.819
to teach it, because the
money's just not very good.

00:05:55.819 --> 00:05:57.360
If you come out of
engineering school

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:00.320
and you can get a job making
what you guys make here

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:04.290
or get a job making a third
of that going to a facility

00:06:04.290 --> 00:06:08.250
where the paint's peeling
and it smells like urine

00:06:08.250 --> 00:06:13.170
and some people literally
are carrying weapons,

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:13.970
what would you do?

00:06:13.970 --> 00:06:17.340
I mean, if I were
king of the forest.

00:06:17.340 --> 00:06:18.650
And I'm not.

00:06:18.650 --> 00:06:21.440
But the longest journey
starts with a single step.

00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:25.750
So our first problem is
educating science educators.

00:06:25.750 --> 00:06:29.449
But if you have school
boards-- in other words,

00:06:29.449 --> 00:06:30.990
we have to do
everything all at once.

00:06:30.990 --> 00:06:34.430
If you have school boards who
are insisting that creationism

00:06:34.430 --> 00:06:40.659
be put in textbooks, then
that's a hard row to hoe.

00:06:40.659 --> 00:06:41.450
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Yeah.

00:06:41.450 --> 00:06:42.864
BILL NYE: But
we've got to do it.

00:06:42.864 --> 00:06:44.280
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Well,
to what extent

00:06:44.280 --> 00:06:47.319
is this actually a uniquely
American phenomenon?

00:06:47.319 --> 00:06:48.860
Has this happened
in other countries?

00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:50.520
BILL NYE: Doesn't seem to.

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:55.560
And you can see on that
gross domestic product chart,

00:06:55.560 --> 00:06:59.980
or handwritten graph-- no,
really, whatever you call it.

00:06:59.980 --> 00:07:02.020
The thing.

00:07:02.020 --> 00:07:03.420
How do we use the word "chart?"

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:04.130
It's a graph.

00:07:04.130 --> 00:07:05.520
It's a depiction.

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:08.694
You see that industrialized
countries, in general,

00:07:08.694 --> 00:07:10.110
believe in the
process of science,

00:07:10.110 --> 00:07:12.359
and evolution is the main
idea in all of life science,

00:07:12.359 --> 00:07:14.540
so they believe in that, too.

00:07:14.540 --> 00:07:17.100
But as I say, evolution
is not something

00:07:17.100 --> 00:07:19.720
you can choose
not to believe in.

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:24.330
I mean, this gets to
be sarcastic and weird.

00:07:24.330 --> 00:07:28.675
You can choose not to believe
in gravity for a few moments.

00:07:33.410 --> 00:07:36.510
But you'll see pretty quickly,
if you jump off a building,

00:07:36.510 --> 00:07:40.266
you'll see right away,
you're headed for trouble.

00:07:40.266 --> 00:07:41.140
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Indeed.

00:07:41.140 --> 00:07:42.598
BILL NYE: It's not
the fall, right?

00:07:42.598 --> 00:07:44.442
Ha, ha, ha, ha.

00:07:44.442 --> 00:07:46.120
It's the sudden stop.

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:50.310
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So let's
get into the topic

00:07:50.310 --> 00:07:52.620
of your book a little bit now.

00:07:52.620 --> 00:07:54.360
So you wrote this book--

00:07:54.360 --> 00:07:56.500
BILL NYE: No, I'm
really proud of it, man.

00:07:56.500 --> 00:07:58.833
VIKRAM BAJAJ: --partly to
address that problem, I think.

00:07:58.833 --> 00:07:59.830
But who's the audience?

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:00.650
Who do you want to read this--

00:08:00.650 --> 00:08:02.275
BILL NYE: Everybody
in the whole world.

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:07.675
So I'll tell the story.

00:08:07.675 --> 00:08:11.540
It's not very long,
thank goodness.

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:16.250
So my friends call
me Shiny Object Man.

00:08:16.250 --> 00:08:18.040
It's a little bit of a problem.

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:20.970
So when you go to sit down
to write a book that's

00:08:20.970 --> 00:08:25.130
going to have 100,000 words
or something in a row,

00:08:25.130 --> 00:08:26.590
you have to be disciplined.

00:08:26.590 --> 00:08:29.740
So I was looking for
an editor to help me.

00:08:29.740 --> 00:08:32.470
And the guy I came across
through mutual acquaintances

00:08:32.470 --> 00:08:35.880
in the business, a guy
named Corey Powell.

00:08:35.880 --> 00:08:36.860
And he's a cool guy.

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:38.790
He was editor of
"Discover Magazine"

00:08:38.790 --> 00:08:42.140
and contributes to
"Scientific American."

00:08:42.140 --> 00:08:44.720
He also contributes
to another magazine

00:08:44.720 --> 00:08:47.790
you may not know called
"American Scientist."

00:08:47.790 --> 00:08:51.400
And he said, what we've
got to do is bottle,

00:08:51.400 --> 00:08:55.000
bottle what you talk about,
and put it in a book.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.840
And that worked out really well.

00:08:57.840 --> 00:09:00.220
But when he was trying
to decide whether or not

00:09:00.220 --> 00:09:03.490
to work with Shiny
Object Man over dinner,

00:09:03.490 --> 00:09:05.690
he asked me why I
was writing the book,

00:09:05.690 --> 00:09:10.920
because according to him-- and
when I watch other television

00:09:10.920 --> 00:09:14.520
shows, people write
books just for the sake

00:09:14.520 --> 00:09:16.505
of having written a book.

00:09:16.505 --> 00:09:18.380
But he asked me, why
did you write this book?

00:09:18.380 --> 00:09:20.336
And I told him I want
to change the world.

00:09:20.336 --> 00:09:21.460
I want to change the world.

00:09:21.460 --> 00:09:22.940
Is that so wrong?

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:24.810
And that's when he
decided to get on board.

00:09:24.810 --> 00:09:26.550
So I wrote it for everybody.

00:09:26.550 --> 00:09:29.950
And I wrote it in English,
as that's my native tongue.

00:09:29.950 --> 00:09:31.110
No, I mean, really.

00:09:31.110 --> 00:09:37.980
And I wrote it in this way that
involves me telling stories

00:09:37.980 --> 00:09:41.840
or anecdotes or
my point of view.

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:43.590
And there's a reason for that.

00:09:43.590 --> 00:09:48.660
First of all, it sounds like me,
which appeals to some people.

00:09:48.660 --> 00:09:50.860
And then the other
thing is, I remember

00:09:50.860 --> 00:09:53.125
the time I met Ivan the gorilla.

00:09:53.125 --> 00:09:54.520
No, you don't.

00:09:54.520 --> 00:09:55.190
Yeah, I do.

00:09:55.190 --> 00:09:56.760
Yes, I do remember.

00:09:56.760 --> 00:09:59.730
And so when you talk
about how you feel,

00:09:59.730 --> 00:10:01.475
people can't disagree with that.

00:10:01.475 --> 00:10:06.160
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So I think
the entrenched opponents

00:10:06.160 --> 00:10:09.610
to your worldview, which is
the evolutionary worldview,

00:10:09.610 --> 00:10:12.500
the worldview that also
believes in gravity--

00:10:12.500 --> 00:10:13.800
BILL NYE: Yeah.

00:10:13.800 --> 00:10:16.360
VIKRAM BAJAJ: --they may not be
your customers for this book.

00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:18.860
But certainly,
people like us, who

00:10:18.860 --> 00:10:22.040
may have occasion to
persuade some of them,

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:24.170
can really benefit
from reading it.

00:10:24.170 --> 00:10:25.600
BILL NYE: Well,
the other thing is

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:32.160
people who are anxious about
it, who are troubled by the idea

00:10:32.160 --> 00:10:36.120
that we are all descendant
from species that

00:10:36.120 --> 00:10:38.470
came before-- 90% of
everything that's ever lived

00:10:38.470 --> 00:10:42.340
has disappeared-- people
who are troubled by that,

00:10:42.340 --> 00:10:44.640
I hope they read
the book, because I

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:46.060
think it's empowering.

00:10:46.060 --> 00:10:48.900
And the process of evolution
fills me with reverence.

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:52.070
I mean, my goodness.

00:10:52.070 --> 00:10:58.980
Just to drop another name, I
had astronomy from Carl Sagan.

00:10:58.980 --> 00:10:59.480
And--

00:10:59.480 --> 00:11:01.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:04.430
I did.

00:11:04.430 --> 00:11:07.100
Look, you guys, I was just some
guy in the back of the room.

00:11:07.100 --> 00:11:09.558
"The Solar System"-- that was
the name of the course, still

00:11:09.558 --> 00:11:11.160
is the name of course.

00:11:11.160 --> 00:11:12.930
And I was in the
back of the room.

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:15.140
I did OK.

00:11:15.140 --> 00:11:15.670
No, I did.

00:11:15.670 --> 00:11:17.086
I was not, like,
the star student.

00:11:17.086 --> 00:11:19.090
I did OK.

00:11:19.090 --> 00:11:23.010
But he was the guy who
really imbued in me,

00:11:23.010 --> 00:11:25.130
or gave me the
fundamental understanding

00:11:25.130 --> 00:11:28.750
that, since you and I
are made of exploded

00:11:28.750 --> 00:11:34.830
stars, the dust of exploded
stars, you and I, all of us,

00:11:34.830 --> 00:11:39.180
are somehow at least one
way that the universe has

00:11:39.180 --> 00:11:41.980
come to know itself.

00:11:41.980 --> 00:11:44.730
And that is amazing.

00:11:44.730 --> 00:11:46.190
That is amazing.

00:11:46.190 --> 00:11:49.920
And every day, it fills
me with reverence.

00:11:49.920 --> 00:11:55.614
And maybe more to the point,
it, like, freaks me out.

00:11:55.614 --> 00:11:57.780
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So your choice
of the word "reverence"

00:11:57.780 --> 00:11:58.980
is interesting.

00:11:58.980 --> 00:12:02.190
You debated, in
February, I think,

