00:14:31.787 --> 00:14:32.370
BILL NYE: DNA.

00:14:32.370 --> 00:14:33.710
He knew nothing of DNA.

00:14:33.710 --> 00:14:34.030
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Exactly.

00:14:34.030 --> 00:14:34.560
Yes.

00:14:34.560 --> 00:14:37.510
How could he have come up
with such a far-ranging theory

00:14:37.510 --> 00:14:40.270
of such predictive value?

00:14:40.270 --> 00:14:42.620
BILL NYE: He was thoughtful.

00:14:42.620 --> 00:14:45.890
And what's striking is, as so
many people have commented,

00:14:45.890 --> 00:14:48.820
why didn't anybody else
think of it before?

00:14:48.820 --> 00:14:52.480
And it shows you how
many-- or notice it

00:14:52.480 --> 00:14:55.370
before-- how many
expectations must

00:14:55.370 --> 00:14:59.450
be built into each of us,
how many assumptions we make

00:14:59.450 --> 00:15:01.610
about the universe
and our relationship

00:15:01.610 --> 00:15:03.360
to it, the cosmos
and our relationship

00:15:03.360 --> 00:15:07.650
to it, that are just wrong,
and we don't even know it.

00:15:07.650 --> 00:15:13.210
But I did tell the story,
my grandmother lived in,

00:15:13.210 --> 00:15:15.630
looking back, a pretty big
house in Washington, DC.

00:15:15.630 --> 00:15:17.340
It had three bedrooms,
which at that time

00:15:17.340 --> 00:15:18.980
is a pretty big house.

00:15:18.980 --> 00:15:23.790
And so she had boarders,
people who would rent rooms,

00:15:23.790 --> 00:15:28.006
after my uncle and my
dad left the house.

00:15:28.006 --> 00:15:29.380
And there was some
guy that would

00:15:29.380 --> 00:15:32.860
sit at the dinner table
talking about chicken bones.

00:15:32.860 --> 00:15:35.200
And "look how the knee is
just like the human knee,

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:35.950
but it's reversed.

00:15:35.950 --> 00:15:36.700
And isn't this cool?

00:15:36.700 --> 00:15:37.825
And look at this cartilage.

00:15:37.825 --> 00:15:39.210
It's just like human cartilage."

00:15:39.210 --> 00:15:41.890
And my grandmother, who was
quite the naturalist-- she

00:15:41.890 --> 00:15:43.870
would collect wild
flowers; she was really

00:15:43.870 --> 00:15:45.960
something-- thought
that was cool.

00:15:45.960 --> 00:15:49.200
But my grandfather was somehow
deeply troubled by this.

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:54.400
He went to church and stuff
in a very traditional way.

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:57.310
But even this guy noticed
these connections.

00:15:57.310 --> 00:15:59.880
Why didn't anybody else notice
these connections before?

00:15:59.880 --> 00:16:01.780
It was really quite a thing.

00:16:01.780 --> 00:16:03.880
And Darwin realized,
apparently--

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:05.960
I'm not an expert on
Darwin-- but he apparently

00:16:05.960 --> 00:16:12.130
spent a lot of time making sure
he had everything worked out.

00:16:12.130 --> 00:16:15.439
I don't know if you've ever
read "The Origin of Species

00:16:15.439 --> 00:16:16.730
by Means of Natural Selection."

00:16:16.730 --> 00:16:21.910
But he did all these
experiments with roses and bees

00:16:21.910 --> 00:16:27.430
and barnacles-- he was just
really into it-- to make sure

00:16:27.430 --> 00:16:30.170
what he was observing, his
hypothesis, was correct.

00:16:30.170 --> 00:16:34.340
And then this guy Russel
Wallace-- and there's

00:16:34.340 --> 00:16:37.110
a whole bunch of people, and
I'm right there with you,

00:16:37.110 --> 00:16:40.372
who celebrate Russel Wallace,
as he came up with the same idea

00:16:40.372 --> 00:16:41.080
at the same time.

00:16:41.080 --> 00:16:43.140
And why isn't there a
Russel Wallace Society,

00:16:43.140 --> 00:16:45.220
and when will we have
Russel Wallace day,

00:16:45.220 --> 00:16:47.350
and why isn't Russell
Wallace on our dollar bills?

00:16:47.350 --> 00:16:49.190
OK.

00:16:49.190 --> 00:16:52.080
He was 16 years
younger than Darwin.

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:54.730
Darwin had a little
head start on him.

00:16:54.730 --> 00:16:59.070
And Darwin's book, where
he's got both the hypothesis,

00:16:59.070 --> 00:17:01.550
or the theory, of evolution
and the experiments

00:17:01.550 --> 00:17:03.170
backing it up in one volume.

00:17:03.170 --> 00:17:06.045
That's way Darwin's name
is so closely tied--

00:17:06.045 --> 00:17:08.420
VIKRAM BAJAJ: And it's a very
accessible book even today.

00:17:08.420 --> 00:17:09.045
BILL NYE: Yeah.

00:17:09.045 --> 00:17:11.810
Even now, it's very readable.

00:17:11.810 --> 00:17:14.099
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Well, why
isn't Darwin on any currency?

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:15.599
BILL NYE: Well,
he is in Britain.

00:17:15.599 --> 00:17:16.829
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Is he?

00:17:16.829 --> 00:17:21.180
BILL NYE: Darwin's on
dollar-- on dollar bills--

00:17:21.180 --> 00:17:23.951
on bills in Britain.

00:17:23.951 --> 00:17:25.200
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Oh, interesting.

00:17:25.200 --> 00:17:27.190
So can you take us
through some of the more

00:17:27.190 --> 00:17:29.650
contemporary evidence
for Darwin's theories?

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:31.910
Let's start with geology
and the fossil record.

00:17:31.910 --> 00:17:33.618
I know you do this
very well in the book.

00:17:33.618 --> 00:17:38.430
BILL NYE: Well, you guys, I went
to school in Ithaca, New York.

00:17:38.430 --> 00:17:40.510
And you can walk
around in Ithaca--

00:17:40.510 --> 00:17:43.930
you don't have to be any
sort of amazing geology guy--

00:17:43.930 --> 00:17:47.700
and you can find trilobite
fossils, zillions of them.

00:17:47.700 --> 00:17:51.120
Trilobites lived something
like 238 million years--

00:17:51.120 --> 00:17:55.520
way longer than humans have been
on Earth by a factor of 100,

00:17:55.520 --> 00:17:59.124
I guess-- factor of 100,
not 100, a factor of 100.

00:17:59.124 --> 00:18:00.540
And so you find
all those fossils.

00:18:00.540 --> 00:18:03.630
Well, how'd they all get
there, for crying out loud?

00:18:03.630 --> 00:18:05.450
And then Darwin
wrestled with this.

00:18:05.450 --> 00:18:09.910
And how does a new species
come into existence?

00:18:09.910 --> 00:18:13.142
And it's just a cool story.

00:18:13.142 --> 00:18:15.600
I don't know if you know about
the mosquitoes in the London

00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:18.220
Underground, the Tube.

00:18:18.220 --> 00:18:21.215
So apparently, the mosquitoes
were living in the underground

00:18:21.215 --> 00:18:24.070
when they dug all these
tunnels in the late 1800s.

00:18:24.070 --> 00:18:25.980
There were mosquitoes
living down there.

00:18:25.980 --> 00:18:29.797
And they would feed on
people like you and me.

00:18:29.797 --> 00:18:32.130
And they would generally-- I
mean, if you're a mosquito,

00:18:32.130 --> 00:18:34.440
you feed on a few people, and
then they close the subway, you

00:18:34.440 --> 00:18:36.850
go back upstairs at night and
feed on some other people.

00:18:36.850 --> 00:18:40.300
But then, when World
War II came along,

00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:45.449
they used the underground
stations as bomb shelters.

00:18:45.449 --> 00:18:46.490
And it's quite effective.

00:18:46.490 --> 00:18:50.540
I mean, getting
bombed kind of sucks.

00:18:50.540 --> 00:18:51.740
But it was quite effective.

00:18:51.740 --> 00:18:58.850
But this really accelerated
the certain mosquitoes.

00:18:58.850 --> 00:19:01.790
Pipiens has become molestus.

00:19:01.790 --> 00:19:05.300
The mosquitoes that
buzzes, pipien,

00:19:05.300 --> 00:19:08.420
has become the
mosquito that annoys.

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:10.780
So there's apparently
a new species

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:15.640
of mosquito evolving in the
London Underground right now.

00:19:15.640 --> 00:19:19.060
And furthermore, you
can see the spectrum.

00:19:19.060 --> 00:19:21.920
Most of the underground
mosquitoes cannot breed with

00:19:21.920 --> 00:19:22.670
the above grounds.

00:19:22.670 --> 00:19:26.960
So the pipiens cannot
breed with the molestus.

00:19:26.960 --> 00:19:30.400
But there are a
few that still can.

00:19:30.400 --> 00:19:34.210
Like you can see that there's
a spectrum of this new species

00:19:34.210 --> 00:19:35.960
coming into existence,
like in real time,

00:19:35.960 --> 00:19:38.800
like in one person's lifetime.

00:19:38.800 --> 00:19:40.480
And that's amazing.

00:19:40.480 --> 00:19:41.150
That's amazing.

00:19:41.150 --> 00:19:44.850
It's not surprising,
really, but it's amazing.

00:19:44.850 --> 00:19:47.809
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So what connects
these contemporary examples

00:19:47.809 --> 00:19:50.100
of speciation-- and there
are a couple that you go over

00:19:50.100 --> 00:19:52.990
in your book,
including evolution

00:19:52.990 --> 00:19:55.280
of antibiotic resistance
and other things short

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:56.960
of speciation--
what connects that

00:19:56.960 --> 00:19:58.990
with this historical
fossil record?

