00:20:02.747 --> 00:20:03.580
BILL NYE: Oh, I see.

00:20:03.580 --> 00:20:07.470
Well, yeah, how many people
have not taken geology?

00:20:07.470 --> 00:20:08.720
I don't know you guys.

00:20:08.720 --> 00:20:11.040
I don't know how you live.

00:20:11.040 --> 00:20:14.290
I don't know anything
about your habits.

00:20:14.290 --> 00:20:19.080
But you'll find that the older
dirty clothes that you've

00:20:19.080 --> 00:20:24.210
discarded on the floor are
underneath the more recent

00:20:24.210 --> 00:20:24.975
dirty clothes.

00:20:30.310 --> 00:20:36.920
And the same is true in geology
with respect to sediments

00:20:36.920 --> 00:20:38.159
and overlays and so on.

00:20:38.159 --> 00:20:39.950
And I'm not the world's
foremost geologist,

00:20:39.950 --> 00:20:42.241
but I can tell you the stuff
at the bottom of the Grand

00:20:42.241 --> 00:20:45.570
Canyon's older than
the stuff at the top.

00:20:45.570 --> 00:20:48.510
I don't make the
rules, as we say.

00:20:48.510 --> 00:20:53.350
The other just amazing thing
that was sort of discovered,

00:20:53.350 --> 00:20:58.140
really, in my father's lifetime,
my grandfather's lifetime,

00:20:58.140 --> 00:21:01.204
is radioactivity and how
you can work backwards.

00:21:01.204 --> 00:21:03.120
And people throw out the
word "carbon dating."

00:21:03.120 --> 00:21:04.786
Carbon dating, it's
fine, but that's not

00:21:04.786 --> 00:21:05.990
what we're talking about.

00:21:05.990 --> 00:21:08.610
Carbon dating is good on, like,
tens of thousands of years.

00:21:08.610 --> 00:21:11.930
Radiometric dating,
where you have-- I mean,

00:21:11.930 --> 00:21:14.710
who doesn't love
rubidium and strontium?

00:21:14.710 --> 00:21:17.460
These are elements
that are out there.

00:21:17.460 --> 00:21:19.250
And they're radioactive.

00:21:19.250 --> 00:21:21.410
And I like that
one in many ways.

00:21:21.410 --> 00:21:26.160
First of all, its half-life
of rubidium becoming strontium

00:21:26.160 --> 00:21:32.520
is 48.8 billion years--
b-- billion years.

00:21:32.520 --> 00:21:37.650
And it's a case where one
of the neutrons in rubidium

00:21:37.650 --> 00:21:38.950
becomes a proton.

00:21:38.950 --> 00:21:41.640
It goes up the periodic table,
giving off some electrons

00:21:41.640 --> 00:21:42.400
and neutrinos.

00:21:42.400 --> 00:21:45.330
Who wouldn't?

00:21:45.330 --> 00:21:48.500
And so then these
things are chemically

00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:52.660
in the same column on the
periodic table as calcium

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:56.270
and sodium so that, in
the melt, as these guys

00:21:56.270 --> 00:21:58.050
love-- who doesn't
love the melt?

00:21:58.050 --> 00:22:00.050
The melt-- you're talking
about molten rocks.

00:22:00.050 --> 00:22:02.141
You're talking about
Hawaii or someplace.

00:22:02.141 --> 00:22:03.390
These things are all mixed in.

00:22:03.390 --> 00:22:06.320
But once they freeze,
once it cools off,

00:22:06.320 --> 00:22:09.620
then, chemically,
some of the rubidium,

00:22:09.620 --> 00:22:11.120
some of the
strontium, is replaced

00:22:11.120 --> 00:22:14.780
by some of the sodium,
some of the calcium.

00:22:14.780 --> 00:22:17.120
And then you can work
this clock backwards.

00:22:17.120 --> 00:22:19.510
This is amazing, It's amazing.

00:22:19.510 --> 00:22:22.530
And that was discovered
long after Darwin's writing

00:22:22.530 --> 00:22:23.890
this book.

00:22:23.890 --> 00:22:26.430
I mean, it's just cool.

00:22:26.430 --> 00:22:28.360
Just think what else
we just don't know

00:22:28.360 --> 00:22:31.280
anything about, right
under our noses.

00:22:31.280 --> 00:22:31.780
Wow.

00:22:31.780 --> 00:22:33.780
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Of course,
to believe in that, you

00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:34.630
