00:35:09.070 --> 00:35:10.592
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So biodiversity.

00:35:10.592 --> 00:35:11.550
BILL NYE: Biodiversity.

00:35:11.550 --> 00:35:14.200
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Yeah, how does it
fit into evolutionary theory?

00:35:14.200 --> 00:35:19.910
BILL NYE: Well, it is reasonable
that the longer life has

00:35:19.910 --> 00:35:23.010
been in any one place, the
more diverse it becomes.

00:35:23.010 --> 00:35:29.370
The longer species have been
generating, interacting,

00:35:29.370 --> 00:35:32.100
with humans in the
subway or what have you,

00:35:32.100 --> 00:35:34.240
the more species you get.

00:35:34.240 --> 00:35:37.100
And not surprisingly,
where there's

00:35:37.100 --> 00:35:40.160
the most sunlight, the
most energy coming in

00:35:40.160 --> 00:35:42.565
from outer space, that's
where the most diversity is,

00:35:42.565 --> 00:35:45.110
at the equator, or
near the equator.

00:35:45.110 --> 00:35:48.200
In tropical rainforests is where
you have the most diversity.

00:35:48.200 --> 00:35:50.620
Then, as you go north or
south from the equator,

00:35:50.620 --> 00:35:52.390
there's less diversity.

