00:48:17.500 --> 00:48:19.562
You couldn't buy
certain vegetables,

00:48:19.562 --> 00:48:21.020
especially at
certain times a year.

00:48:21.020 --> 00:48:21.769
You just couldn't.

00:48:21.769 --> 00:48:25.690
They weren't available, because
the man stepped in and sent it

00:48:25.690 --> 00:48:29.870
to the boys to conduct the war.

00:48:29.870 --> 00:48:32.770
And that was government
intrusion in a way

00:48:32.770 --> 00:48:36.512
that-- people talk about
the greatest generation.

00:48:36.512 --> 00:48:38.595
Part of the reason that
people considered it great

00:48:38.595 --> 00:48:40.200
is because they worked together.

00:48:40.200 --> 00:48:41.710
And to address
climate change, it's

00:48:41.710 --> 00:48:44.030
going to be that same deal.

00:48:44.030 --> 00:48:46.830
The sooner we get started,
the better, for me.

00:48:46.830 --> 00:48:49.380
VIKRAM BAJAJ: And what role
do you see, more specifically,

00:48:49.380 --> 00:48:51.844
for large corporations,
like Google?

00:48:51.844 --> 00:48:52.760
BILL NYE: Like Google?

00:48:52.760 --> 00:48:53.350
Man.

00:48:53.350 --> 00:48:53.680
VIKRAM BAJAJ: What
do you want us to do?

00:48:53.680 --> 00:48:55.179
BILL NYE: No, the
key to the future,

00:48:55.179 --> 00:48:57.270
kids, peoples, you are it.

00:48:57.270 --> 00:48:58.781
You are IT.

00:48:58.781 --> 00:48:59.280
Wait.

00:49:02.280 --> 00:49:03.650
No.

00:49:03.650 --> 00:49:06.440
No, you are it, because
the key to the future

00:49:06.440 --> 00:49:09.150
is not just to do less.

00:49:09.150 --> 00:49:13.730
I grew up-- I'm so old-- I
remember the very first Earth

00:49:13.730 --> 00:49:14.820
Day.

00:49:14.820 --> 00:49:22.000
The very first Earth Day was
in 1970, before Motown really

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:25.220
was called Motown.

00:49:25.220 --> 00:49:28.755
The Motor City existed, but
the music, although it existed,

00:49:28.755 --> 00:49:29.880
didn't have that sobriquet.

00:49:29.880 --> 00:49:32.460
Anyway-- digress, me?

00:49:34.630 --> 00:49:36.630
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Or perhaps
there's no easy answer.

00:49:36.630 --> 00:49:37.338
BILL NYE: No, no.

00:49:37.338 --> 00:49:40.950
So in those days, everybody
wanted you to do less,

00:49:40.950 --> 00:49:46.620
to drive your car less,
to use less clean water,

00:49:46.620 --> 00:49:48.650
so wear dirty clothes.

00:49:48.650 --> 00:49:50.110
And humans are bad.

00:49:50.110 --> 00:49:52.070
Humans don't belong
in the ecosystem,

00:49:52.070 --> 00:49:56.270
humans have nothing to do with
nature, get rid of humans.

00:49:56.270 --> 00:49:58.560
In fact, if you
can, just don't eat.

00:49:58.560 --> 00:49:59.830
Don't even eat, really.

00:49:59.830 --> 00:50:01.288
And that's turned
out to be, as you

00:50:01.288 --> 00:50:03.290
might imagine, not
especially popular.

00:50:03.290 --> 00:50:06.150
And so the key to the
future is not to do less.

00:50:06.150 --> 00:50:09.290
The key is to do more with less.

00:50:09.290 --> 00:50:11.020
And that's where
companies like Google

00:50:11.020 --> 00:50:14.150
enable this in an amazing way.

00:50:14.150 --> 00:50:17.030
Do you know how many
hours people my age

00:50:17.030 --> 00:50:19.560
spent in the freaking library?

00:50:19.560 --> 00:50:21.840
I mean, going to look
things up in a card catalog

00:50:21.840 --> 00:50:23.950
was a skill you developed.

00:50:23.950 --> 00:50:26.495
But the difference was,
when you found stuff

00:50:26.495 --> 00:50:28.130
in the encyclopedia--
if you found

00:50:28.130 --> 00:50:34.000
the atomic number
of strontium-- 38--

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:36.740
in the Encyclopedia
Britannica, it

00:50:36.740 --> 00:50:38.540
was almost certainly correct.

00:50:38.540 --> 00:50:40.160
There was no issue with that.

00:50:40.160 --> 00:50:42.615
Whereas now, when you
look on Wikipedia,

00:50:42.615 --> 00:50:44.490
you just don't know what
you're going to get.

00:50:44.490 --> 00:50:48.720
So it's a new skill that
students have to develop,

00:50:48.720 --> 00:50:52.750
is how to sift through this
greater volume of lower quality

00:50:52.750 --> 00:50:53.340
information.

00:50:53.340 --> 00:50:56.190
But the world will be better,
because not everybody has

00:50:56.190 --> 00:50:58.350
to get in the car or
the subway to commute.

00:50:58.350 --> 00:51:02.234
People can commute
from their phone.

00:51:02.234 --> 00:51:04.150
The planetary side,
people are extraordinarily

00:51:04.150 --> 00:51:06.794
productive without ever coming
into the office, I have to say.

00:51:06.794 --> 00:51:08.210
But that doesn't
mean I don't want

00:51:08.210 --> 00:51:09.370
you coming into the
office, you guys.

00:51:09.370 --> 00:51:10.680
I'm sorry, if you're out there.

00:51:13.260 --> 00:51:18.690
And so Google is a key
to doing more with less.

00:51:18.690 --> 00:51:20.830
But somewhere along
the line, you guys,

00:51:20.830 --> 00:51:23.630
somebody's going to have
to make electricity.

00:51:23.630 --> 00:51:25.560
You can have all the
server farms you want,

00:51:25.560 --> 00:51:30.240
but if you can't plug them
in, we're in bad shape.

00:51:30.240 --> 00:51:32.820
And this is when-- is
it true that robots

00:51:32.820 --> 00:51:36.330
are going to take
over the world?

00:51:36.330 --> 00:51:38.870
I mean, if somebody keeps
shoveling coal for them,

00:51:38.870 --> 00:51:40.760
I guess.

00:51:40.760 --> 00:51:42.280
But if you stop
making electricity,

00:51:42.280 --> 00:51:44.960
the robots will really have
a hard time of it, generally.

00:51:44.960 --> 00:51:46.770
No, they'll make
nuclear power plants.

00:51:46.770 --> 00:51:48.600
OK, all right, maybe.

00:51:48.600 --> 00:51:50.980
It's not so simple.

00:51:50.980 --> 00:51:51.820
So go ahead.

00:51:51.820 --> 00:51:54.180
Sorry.

00:51:54.180 --> 00:51:54.720
Hold it.

00:51:54.720 --> 00:51:57.670
It says right here, we're
not going to do any-- whoa,

00:51:57.670 --> 00:51:58.610
I've blown it.

00:51:58.610 --> 00:51:59.210
Sorry.

00:51:59.210 --> 00:51:59.580
Go ahead.

00:51:59.580 --> 00:52:01.320
VIKRAM BAJAJ: So there
is really no easy answer.

00:52:01.320 --> 00:52:03.540
It's something that we
all have to struggle to--

00:52:03.540 --> 00:52:06.500
BILL NYE: Well, when it comes to
climate change, in my opinion,

00:52:06.500 --> 00:52:11.540
the answer is to do everything
we possibly can, all at once.

00:52:11.540 --> 00:52:13.410
How's that?

00:52:13.410 --> 00:52:16.590
More efficient electricity,
more efficient trans--

00:52:16.590 --> 00:52:18.590
transportation is a
huge cost, especially

00:52:18.590 --> 00:52:24.870
in the US-- more efficient
cities, more efficient farms,

00:52:24.870 --> 00:52:28.310
in the biggest picture,
and of course, raising

00:52:28.310 --> 00:52:32.330
the quality of life,
especially of women and girls,

00:52:32.330 --> 00:52:35.750
because deep within
this problem--

00:52:35.750 --> 00:52:42.610
when I was here at the
World's Fair, in 1965,

00:52:42.610 --> 00:52:45.920
I was nine years old,
the world had just

00:52:45.920 --> 00:52:48.847
gotten 3 billion people.

00:52:48.847 --> 00:52:50.180
Well, a few days ago, I checked.

00:52:50.180 --> 00:52:52.720
We're at 7.2 billion people.

00:52:52.720 --> 00:52:54.450
And that's it.

00:52:54.450 --> 00:52:56.350
You've more than doubled
the number of humans

00:52:56.350 --> 00:52:59.420
burning and breathing the
atmosphere in the last two

00:52:59.420 --> 00:53:00.120
decades.

00:53:00.120 --> 00:53:01.570
That's your problem.

00:53:01.570 --> 00:53:06.410
So we need to reduce
the human population.

00:53:06.410 --> 00:53:07.120
We do.

00:53:07.120 --> 00:53:10.120
But I mean, this is--
you guys, we don't do it.

00:53:10.120 --> 00:53:14.290
By the way, war is
completely ineffective.

00:53:14.290 --> 00:53:16.510
Ebola will not do it.

00:53:16.510 --> 00:53:18.270
No.

00:53:18.270 --> 00:53:19.690
And you can see it historically.

00:53:19.690 --> 00:53:21.320
The scale of the
problem is huge.

00:53:21.320 --> 00:53:24.620
Well, if you raise the standard
of living of women and girls,

00:53:24.620 --> 00:53:26.830
over the next
century and a half,

00:53:26.830 --> 00:53:29.059
the human population will
stabilize and go down.

00:53:29.059 --> 00:53:29.850
VIKRAM BAJAJ: Sure.

00:53:29.850 --> 00:53:32.590
BILL NYE: And the way to do that
is to educate women and girls.

00:53:32.590 --> 00:53:35.080
This is a really huge problem.

00:53:35.080 --> 00:53:36.520
But let's get going, people.

00:53:36.520 --> 00:53:38.764
We can change the world.

00:53:38.764 --> 00:53:40.240
AUDIENCE: Whoo, yeah.

00:53:40.240 --> 00:53:43.684
